487:     private void updateInputPartitionsOfStandbyTaskIfTheyChanged(final Task task,
488:                                                                  final Set<TopicPartition> inputPartitions) {
489:         /*
490:         We should only update input partitions of a standby task if the input partitions really changed. Updating the
491:         input partitions of tasks also updates the mapping from source nodes to input topics in the processor topology
492:         within the task. The mapping is updated with the topics from the topology metadata. The topology metadata does
493:         not prefix intermediate internal topics with the application ID. Thus, if a standby task has input partitions
494:         from an intermediate internal topic the update of the mapping in the processor topology leads to an invalid
495:         topology exception during recycling of a standby task to an active task when the input queues are created. This
496:         is because the input topics in the processor topology and the input partitions of the task do not match because
497:         the former miss the application ID prefix.
498:         For standby task that have only input partitions from intermediate internal topics this check avoids the invalid
499:         topology exception. Unfortunately, a subtopology might have input partitions subscribed to with a regex
500:         additionally intermediate internal topics which might still lead to an invalid topology exception during recycling
